messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full path(s) and allowed methods derived from the code:

1) Path: /profiles
- all methods acceptable: false
- HEAD: false
- POST: true
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: false
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

Notes: GET /profiles is implemented as getProfilesByUser and expects a query parameter (searchQuery) to find the profile for a given user. The route for listing all profiles (getProfiles) is present in the controller but commented out in routes/profile.js, so it is NOT active.

2) Path: /profiles/{id}
- all methods acceptable: false
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: false
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: true

Explanation / reasoning:
- index.js mounts the profile router at the /profiles prefix: app.use('/profiles', profile).
- routes/profile.js registers the following active routes:
  - router.get('/:id', getProfile) => GET /profiles/{id}
  - router.get('/', getProfilesByUser) => GET /profiles (uses query param searchQuery)
  - router.post('/', createProfile) => POST /profiles
  - router.patch('/:id', updateProfile) => PATCH /profiles/{id}
  - router.delete('/:id', deleteProfile) => DELETE /profiles/{id}
  - The router.get('/', getProfiles) route is commented out, so GET /profiles for listing all profiles is not active.
- There are no router.all, router.put, router.head, router.options, or router.trace handlers defined for these routes in the code, so those methods are marked false. (Although some servers/frameworks implicitly handle HEAD for existing GET routes, this answer does not assume implicit behavior and follows only the explicit code.)
